Use `jazz-testing` only. Start a real local server, connect two in-memory clients, write several rows from client A, wait for `edge`, then assert on client B with a retrying check that normalizes order by a stable key before comparing.

```ts
import { createDb } from "jazz-tools";
import { startLocalJazzServer, deploy } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { beforeEach, afterEach, it, expect, vi } from "vitest";
import { app } from "../schema";

let server;
let alice;
let bob;

beforeEach(async () => {
  server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  await deploy({
    serverUrl: server.url,
    appId: server.appId,
    adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
    schema: app,
  });
  alice = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });
  bob = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await alice?.shutdown();
  await bob?.shutdown();
  await server?.stop();
});

it("syncs several rows deterministically without depending on query order", async () => {
  const expected = [
    { slug: "a", title: "Alpha" },
    { slug: "b", title: "Beta" },
    { slug: "c", title: "Gamma" },
  ];

  for (const row of expected) {
    await alice.insert(app.todos, row).wait({ tier: "edge" });
  }

  await vi.waitFor(async () => {
    const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
    const normalized = rows
      .map((r) => ({ slug: r.slug, title: r.title }))
      .sort((l, r) => l.slug.localeCompare(r.slug));

    expect(normalized).toEqual(expected);
  });
});
```

If the schema has no stable key like `slug`, explicitly query with ordering if supported; otherwise normalize by `id` or another deterministic field.

Use `jazz-testing` only. For a row policy, use `createPolicyTestApp`, create Alice and Bob sessions, insert through Alice so ownership is recorded via the public API, then assert Bob gets filtered reads and rejected writes.

```ts
import { createPolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { beforeEach, afterEach, it, expect } from "vitest";
import { app } from "../schema";
import permissions from "../permissions";

let testApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

it("denies Bob read and write access to Alice's row", async () => {
  const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
  const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });

  const row = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Alice private" }).value;

  await expect(bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);
  bob.expectDenied((db) => db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Bob edit" }));
  bob.expectDenied((db) => db.delete(app.todos, row.id));

  await expect(alice.all(app.todos.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toEqual([
    expect.objectContaining({ id: row.id, title: "Alice private" }),
  ]);
});
```

If ownership-sensitive updates exist, add a separate case asserting Bob cannot change the row into a state that would grant himself access, and keep denied reads asserted as empty results rather than exceptions.
